WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.800
My first actual data science job was literally the result of waking up from a dream.

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:06.560
How does that lead you to where you are now?

00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:09.520
I had an experience that I think a lot of data scientists have,

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:13.200
which is getting sort of inexorably dragged down the stack.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.920
What I wanted to do was do all this cool data science that would like make a difference,

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:22.080
but what it kept turning out I had to do was make the data better.

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:26.400
Are there any key factors for improving voter turnout?

00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:30.240
Turns out that working for political campaigns is like really exhausting

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:32.560
because everything is on fire all the time.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:34.240
It's an interesting data problem.

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:35.840
How do you fund open source software?

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:40.799
And there have been a lot of different models to try and fund open source software.

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:44.000
And the reality is, unfortunately, that most of them kind of suck.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.840
What do you think the state of the language war is now?

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:51.599
I don't understand why people like put up with Jupyter Notebooks.

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:53.360
Like y'all can have nice things too.

00:00:56.400 --> 00:01:03.680
This episode of Ken's Serious Neighbors is powered by Z by HP,

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:07.199
HP's high compute workstation grade line of products and solutions.

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:09.839
Today, I have the pleasure of interviewing Alex Gold.

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:13.440
So Alex recently published the book DevOps for Data Science.

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:16.559
And in this episode, we're going to dive into a little bit of what DevOps is,

00:01:16.559 --> 00:01:19.599
what it isn't, and how it might be different from MLOps,

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:22.160
which we've talked at length about on the podcast.

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:24.320
Alex also has had a very interesting career.

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:28.400
He's currently the director of solutions engineering at Posit.

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:33.040
And we're going to ask some questions about what solution engineering is,

00:01:33.599 --> 00:01:35.919
who might be a good fit for those types of roles,

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:38.400
and what opportunities are available there.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:42.480
We'll also dive into some of the details on the language wars.

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.680
Obviously, Alex works at Posit.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:49.839
So he has a little bit of a strong take on the R versus Python debate.

00:01:49.839 --> 00:01:52.720
I really enjoyed this conversation with Alex, and I'm sure you will as well.

00:01:53.279 --> 00:01:56.480
Alex, welcome to the Ken's Nearest Neighbors podcast.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:57.440
Thank you so much for coming on.

00:01:57.440 --> 00:01:58.160
It's great to be here.

00:01:58.160 --> 00:01:59.360
Thanks for having me.

00:02:00.559 --> 00:02:01.040
Of course.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.760
So we met through some mutual friends at Posit.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:04.160
Yeah.

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:06.000
Obviously, I've worked with them a lot.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.440
Well, you guys a lot in the past, and you have a book coming out.

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.160
I wanted to learn a little bit more, one, about your story,

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:17.520
and two, a little bit more about the overarching process and your book in general.

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:21.119
So I'd love, before we get into all of those wonderful things,

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:24.639
I'd love to first start with a little bit of background on yourself.

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:25.279
Yeah.

00:02:25.279 --> 00:02:29.440
Maybe let's dive into where you first got interested in data.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:30.160
Sounds great.

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:30.479
Yeah.

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:37.360
So my background, my undergrad was in math and econ.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:39.199
I went to Wesleyan University.

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:40.000
They don't have minors.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:40.800
At least they didn't at the time.

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:43.520
So there was this funny, like, it was not quite a double major,

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:47.440
but it was like a major and a minor in math and econ, econ and math, that order.

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:49.520
That was one thing.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:50.160
Maybe it's still there.

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:51.679
I don't know if there are Wesleyan people listening.

00:02:51.679 --> 00:02:53.119
I'd be curious to know if it's still a thing.

00:02:53.679 --> 00:02:57.600
But so that's what I did.

00:02:57.600 --> 00:03:01.679
And the thing I thought was really cool about economics,

00:03:01.679 --> 00:03:06.000
and the reason I, like, really loved it, is that it was numbers, it was math,

00:03:06.639 --> 00:03:08.960
but it was about the real world, right?

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:11.440
It was not just sort of math for its own sake.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:19.360
It was really, you know, related to things that people care about in their day-to-day lives.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:25.679
And so I spent the first few years of my career working in sort of the economic policy world

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:27.600
in Washington, D.C.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:31.759
I worked at a couple different think tanks and found myself, you know,

00:03:31.759 --> 00:03:37.440
I did some data-related stuff, some just, like, general, you know, qualitative policy work.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:41.279
Found myself enjoying the data part much more.

00:03:41.279 --> 00:03:47.440
And then, you know, a few years down the road, I started an econ PhD program and dropped out.

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:55.119
And then a few years later, ended up going sort of all the way into the data world.

00:03:55.119 --> 00:03:57.440
And, you know, it was really more of the same.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:04.960
It was, right, it was numbers, it was math, it was statistics, but it was about the real world.

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:08.399
And that was what was so interesting to me, right?

00:04:08.399 --> 00:04:12.399
Because I got to do these, like, sort of, I think a lot of us who love data, right?

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:14.240
We love, like, the puzzle aspect of it.

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:17.040
You write the code, you get the data to shape, right?

00:04:17.119 --> 00:04:19.440
And then you make that visualization or you build that model.

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:24.239
But I also really liked that it was actually related to the real world and not just,

00:04:24.239 --> 00:04:27.119
sort of, you know, math for its own sake.

00:04:28.399 --> 00:04:30.559
We had a very similar experience there.

00:04:30.559 --> 00:04:34.239
I mean, in college, I remember taking my first econ course,

00:04:34.239 --> 00:04:37.519
and I was honestly a very bad student until that point.

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:39.920
And it all just sort of made sense.

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:43.760
I realized that I could see the world through trends, through graphs,

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:46.320
and I could start to understand it in a very different way.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:48.480
And that was something that really spoke to me.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.079
And it opened the door to saying,

00:04:50.079 --> 00:04:53.760
hey, if this is useful to understand trends in human behavior,

00:04:54.799 --> 00:04:57.519
can I use it to understand my golf game better?

00:04:57.519 --> 00:04:59.440
Can I use it to understand all these different things?

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:07.119
And I remember how powerful that was that sort of opened my mind up to the possibilities of

00:05:08.079 --> 00:05:12.160
math or statistics being an applied thing rather than just a theoretical thing,

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:13.519
which was super, super cool.

00:05:13.839 --> 00:05:14.640
Yeah, absolutely.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:19.679
And I think what's really interesting about data science as a field

00:05:19.679 --> 00:05:22.959
is that I think that's the story of a lot of us

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:25.679
who are in data science or who got into data science.

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:29.200
I mean, these days, there are a lot of data science programs,

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:30.239
which I think is awesome.

00:05:30.239 --> 00:05:32.880
Like, you know, now you can get a bachelor's or a master's.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:33.359
I don't even know.

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:36.799
There may even be doctorate programs in data science, per se.

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:40.320
But, you know, when I was in school, that didn't exist.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:43.839
And so everybody who sort of ended up in data science

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:46.320
was coming from somewhere else.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:49.760
And that's something that I think is really cool about this field

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:55.200
is just how it sort of is this marriage of a lot of really, you know,

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:59.839
interesting statistics, machine learning, computer science kind of stuff.

00:05:59.839 --> 00:06:04.000
And then, like, what can you do with this in the real world?

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:06.559
So, yeah, that totally resonates for me.

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:08.399
Amazing.

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:11.600
Well, so you talked about how you're doing some of these think tanks.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:13.119
You're working in policy in D.C.

00:06:13.119 --> 00:06:16.480
You're working in and dropped out of your Ph.D. program.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:19.600
How does that lead you to where you are now?

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:20.640
Yeah, yeah.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:23.200
So there's another hop after that.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:29.440
So my sort of policy world led me into data science.

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:32.160
And my first data science job was a political job,

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:35.040
doing work on political campaigns.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:38.239
So that was sort of like a little hop into data science.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:42.160
Then I had another role after that in data science,

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:43.679
more like generic data science.

00:06:43.679 --> 00:06:45.600
I was working for a big consulting firm,

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:48.239
did some work with hospital systems,

00:06:48.239 --> 00:06:50.000
did some work with the Social Security Administration.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:53.760
And that was, you know, sort of general data science.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:55.920
I ended up leading a team in that role.

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:02.079
And then from there, you know, I had obviously been spending a lot of time

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:06.399
using R, getting excited about the power of programming for data science, right?

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:15.760
Not just the model building or the dashboarding or the visualizations.

00:07:16.559 --> 00:07:18.880
But I had an experience that I think a lot of people,

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:20.559
a lot of data scientists have,

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:25.040
which is getting sort of inexorably dragged down the stack.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:28.720
That like, what I wanted to do was do all this cool data science

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:32.239
that would like make a difference, you know,

00:07:32.239 --> 00:07:34.320
but what it kept turning out I had to do was like,

00:07:35.519 --> 00:07:37.839
make the data better, right?

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:40.799
And then eventually you end up like managing a database.

00:07:40.799 --> 00:07:44.000
And at some point I found myself managing an RStudio server

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.239
because like somebody needed to do it.

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:50.160
And so what I found was I actually kind of enjoyed that part of it, right?

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:52.880
I enjoyed learning about how to like administer a Linux server.

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.920
I enjoyed learning about how sort of database administration worked.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.239
Although I learned like this much about that topic.

00:07:58.239 --> 00:08:03.839
Then what happened honestly is I got connected to some folks at then RStudio,

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:09.359
now Posit, and learned a little bit about solutions engineering

00:08:09.359 --> 00:08:14.640
and made the hop over to then RStudio about five and a half years ago.

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:19.279
And so spent, you know, about a year and a half being a solutions engineer

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:21.679
and happy to talk more about sort of what that means, right?

00:08:21.679 --> 00:08:28.559
But it's sort of this interesting spot about helping our Posit customers

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:32.719
have a great time using the Posit product, right?

00:08:32.719 --> 00:08:38.960
How do you make sure that the environments that data scientists have to work in

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:42.239
are great environments to do data science?

00:08:42.239 --> 00:08:43.840
And so really enjoyed that.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:45.280
And then, you know, I'd been a manager.

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.280
I really enjoyed being a manager.

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:51.679
And when managerial roles opened up, I moved back into management

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:56.159
and have sort of taken on successively bigger management roles.

00:08:56.159 --> 00:08:58.799
And so now at Posit, I lead the solutions engineering

00:08:58.799 --> 00:09:02.799
and the technical support teams, which is really a blast.

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:08.000
So yeah, it's one of those stories that I remember, you know,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.440
when I was, whatever I was, 23, 24 in my first job,

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:16.000
somebody telling me that like careers make no sense lived forward,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.559
but the story makes a lot of sense told backwards.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:20.719
And I really feel like saying this out loud,

00:09:20.719 --> 00:09:22.479
that really resonates for me that like,

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:24.400
oh, that story makes a lot of sense when I tell it this way.

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:27.280
But at the time, it made no sense whatsoever.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:31.679
I'll just share like my first actual data science job

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:35.039
was literally the result of waking up from a dream that I had.

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:38.000
I like woke up, I'd had a dream that I was going to work for,

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:40.559
it was 2015, fall of 2015.

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:41.919
I was like, oh, I'm going to go.

00:09:41.919 --> 00:09:44.239
I had a dream that I was working for the Hillary campaign.

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:46.960
I was like, okay, I'm going to go do political data science stuff.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:48.719
And that was just a complete, it was a great left turn,

00:09:48.719 --> 00:09:50.320
but it was a total left turn for my career.

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:53.679
And it was literally the result of a random dream that I had.

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:56.799
I just like woke up and I was like, oh, what if I actually did that?

00:09:58.719 --> 00:09:59.760
That's fascinating.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:02.559
You know, the more people I talk to on the podcast,

00:10:02.559 --> 00:10:06.479
the more that that really hits home, including in my life.

00:10:06.479 --> 00:10:09.599
I mean, nothing really makes sense until afterwards

00:10:09.599 --> 00:10:12.159
when you look back at it and you put it all together

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:16.320
and going through it, we're all kind of just fumbling through the dark

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:18.239
and trying to figure it all out.

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:21.119
Before I dive into the solutions engineering stuff,

00:10:21.119 --> 00:10:24.719
I'd love to learn more about what you were doing in policy

00:10:24.719 --> 00:10:26.640
and those types of things.

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:30.080
I think that it is election season right now.

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:32.479
And I don't particularly want to get into any politics,

00:10:32.479 --> 00:10:35.840
but I'm interested in the data surrounding the politics

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:38.159
and like what goes into those types of things

00:10:38.159 --> 00:10:41.919
that maybe the traditional, the layman isn't familiar with.

00:10:42.479 --> 00:10:45.760
So I worked in both policy and politics,

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:48.159
which from like, if you're outside of it, you're like,

00:10:48.159 --> 00:10:49.200
those are the same thing, right?

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:51.760
But like, fundamentally, they are quite different, right?

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:58.559
Policy is about what is the government going to do for people or not do, right?

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:00.799
And then politics is about who wins elections.

00:11:00.799 --> 00:11:03.119
And so while they are related, obviously,

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:05.440
you only get to do policy if you win elections.

00:11:06.479 --> 00:11:07.599
If you're on one side or the other,

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:12.640
the sort of practice of it is completely different.

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:17.039
So in the policy world, I did some data work, for example,

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:21.440
where we were using some longitudinal surveys

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:28.080
of basically the economic success achieved by children.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:30.320
So we were trying to do this like very complex modeling.

00:11:31.039 --> 00:11:33.200
If anybody's familiar with the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth,

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:35.520
the NLSY surveys, these are what we used.

00:11:36.239 --> 00:11:40.719
And we built this model that could, at least in theory,

00:11:40.719 --> 00:11:45.200
synthetic, we created a synthetic data set of people from age zero to 40.

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:48.960
Now, there's no actual data set that follows people from zero to 40.

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:52.000
And so we took these several different data sets and stitched them together

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:56.559
with a variety of different sort of like matching, statistical matching techniques

00:11:57.679 --> 00:12:01.840
and other kinds of inference techniques.

00:12:02.239 --> 00:12:06.080
And for what it's worth, I did this all in Stata, which was a real...

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:10.880
I know there are people out there who think like R is a difficult language to work with.

00:12:11.599 --> 00:12:14.080
You should go have some fun with Stata, that's a bear.

00:12:16.479 --> 00:12:18.479
So that was what I did on the policy side.

00:12:18.479 --> 00:12:20.640
So that was really, really interesting.

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:23.039
There are interesting statistical problems.

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:29.039
For the most part, a lot of data on the policy side is smallish data problems, right?

00:12:29.039 --> 00:12:32.960
They're longitudinal surveys, which are very expensive to collect.

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:37.440
Occasionally, you do get larger data sets, like in some later stuff I worked with,

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:41.760
hospital claim data, which is not huge, but it's large, right?

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:48.000
You have like one line of data per every single procedure that happens in a hospital.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:49.440
So you have millions of rows.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.520
You're still in sort of modest size data there.

00:12:53.119 --> 00:12:56.960
In politics, there are a variety of different sources of data.

00:12:56.960 --> 00:12:58.960
One of the biggest ones is something called the voter file,

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:05.599
which people who are not in the political world might be sort of horrified to know exists,

00:13:05.599 --> 00:13:07.359
but it's a standard thing.

00:13:07.359 --> 00:13:10.239
Each secretary of state for every state keeps a voter file,

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:15.119
which is a list of all the people who are registered voters in that state

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:18.000
and when they have voted.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.919
So as we like to say to people, who you vote for is private,

00:13:21.919 --> 00:13:24.640
but whether you voted is a matter of public record.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:31.200
And so there's a lot of work in politics done off of these voter files.

00:13:31.200 --> 00:13:34.719
My understanding is that also a lot of commercial data stuff

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:37.840
starts at the voter file in a lot of cases.

00:13:39.679 --> 00:13:46.640
And so these data files are compiled by state secretaries of state.

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:50.159
There are then companies that go around and gather the data from all 50 states,

00:13:50.159 --> 00:13:54.640
because actually it's like a pain in the ass to homogenize 50 different state voter files.

00:13:55.599 --> 00:13:57.039
And so we were doing a lot of work.

00:13:58.159 --> 00:14:01.200
The role I was in, we were doing voter outreach experiments.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:03.599
And so we were looking at things like,

00:14:03.599 --> 00:14:07.520
does this message or that message make people more likely to go out to vote?

00:14:08.159 --> 00:14:10.320
And so the kind of things we would do is before the election,

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:12.880
we would take the voter file, we would randomize it.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:14.960
And some people would get this piece of mail.

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:16.320
Some people would get that piece of mail.

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:19.119
Some people would get nothing or this text or that text.

00:14:19.119 --> 00:14:22.000
And then after the election, we would gather back up the voter files

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:23.919
and see who voted and who didn't.

00:14:23.919 --> 00:14:29.359
And so they were literal like field experiments on voter outreach.

00:14:29.359 --> 00:14:31.119
This is sort of the gold standard, obviously,

00:14:31.119 --> 00:14:33.520
because it's an actual randomized controlled trial.

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:38.000
But there's just a ton of data stuff going on in politics these days.

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:40.000
Oh, that's fascinating.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.679
I mean, that makes a ton of sense to me.

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:45.440
You think about a lot of the campaigns that are run about getting people to vote,

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:50.000
rather than I would imagine it's a lot easier to get someone to vote

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:53.679
from who's aligned with a specific party

00:14:53.679 --> 00:14:57.039
than to convert someone to vote for a different candidate.

00:14:57.039 --> 00:14:59.760
And it's an interesting data problem of,

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:02.880
hey, let's invest money in just finding people

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:05.679
and getting them to vote versus trying to change opinion,

00:15:05.679 --> 00:15:07.760
which is maybe a little bit sad.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:11.840
I think the idea of having a message that you believe is important

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:14.719
and winning people over that is important.

00:15:14.719 --> 00:15:20.960
But if we think about effectiveness, there's another side to that as well.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:22.239
It's a great point.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:29.760
The organization I worked for was aligned firmly with progressive causes and candidates.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:33.359
And so if that's the side you're on, what you're trying to do

00:15:33.359 --> 00:15:36.719
is you are trying to increase the vote margin for progressive candidates.

00:15:36.719 --> 00:15:40.000
And there are basically three things you could do.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:45.119
You can make people who were going to vote for a Republican vote for a Democrat instead.

00:15:45.919 --> 00:15:48.880
You can make more Democrats or people who are going to vote for Democrats,

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:51.760
at least because very few people actually register these days.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:54.080
They say they're independents, but almost nobody's actually independent.

00:15:55.039 --> 00:15:57.599
And so you take people who are going to vote Democratic

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:00.799
and you get them to come out, or you get the Republicans to stay home.

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:03.359
Those are the three things you can do.

00:16:04.479 --> 00:16:07.039
The third one of those is a little distasteful, I think.

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:10.719
It's sort of some dark side stuff there.

00:16:11.760 --> 00:16:14.080
But those are kind of the three options you have.

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:19.280
And there is a really active, I think, debate, honestly, going on

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:24.000
about whether persuasion, which is getting people to go to the other side,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:29.440
or straight turnout stuff is more useful.

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:31.760
It definitely varies election by election.

00:16:31.760 --> 00:16:33.280
The other thing that's really interesting is, obviously,

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.440
you can do a lot more in a smaller election, right?

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:41.679
So if you're talking about in 2015, 2016, obviously, it was Hillary.

00:16:41.679 --> 00:16:43.039
Trump was the election.

00:16:43.599 --> 00:16:47.599
And most people knew a lot about that election.

00:16:47.599 --> 00:16:50.799
And there really is only so much you can do to affect that.

00:16:51.679 --> 00:16:52.880
They're on the news constantly.

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:54.080
There's a ton of earned media.

00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:59.200
And so do you actually think one mailer is going to change people's minds

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:01.200
on whether they're going to go vote for Hillary or Trump?

00:17:01.919 --> 00:17:02.799
Probably not.

00:17:02.799 --> 00:17:04.319
But when you're talking about down-ballot races,

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:05.839
when you're talking about a state senate race,

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:09.839
or the district attorney in Chicago,

00:17:09.839 --> 00:17:12.000
those are races, actually, where this kind of paid media

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:13.439
can have a much bigger effect,

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:15.680
because people aren't paying as close attention.

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:17.359
Their minds aren't made up ahead of time.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:19.119
They're more persuadable.

00:17:19.119 --> 00:17:22.079
And they might not be planning to vote at all

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:23.920
unless they learn something about the candidates

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:27.199
or are sort of incentivized to come out for it.

