Z is specifically made for high-performance data science solutions,

00:17:38.959 --> 00:17:42.800
and I personally use the ZBook Studio and the Z8 workstation.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:47.439
I really love that the Z workstations can come standard with Linux or WSL2,

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:50.640
and they can be configured with the Data Science Software Stack Manager.

00:17:51.199 --> 00:17:52.880
With the Software Stack Manager,

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.920
you can get right to the work of doing data science on day one

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:00.239
without the overhead of having to completely reconfigure your new machine.

00:18:00.239 --> 00:18:01.280
Now back to our show.

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:05.760
So this might be an impossible-to-answer question,

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:07.599
and it might be highly variable,

00:18:07.599 --> 00:18:09.599
depending where you are, markets, whatever it is.

00:18:09.599 --> 00:18:15.119
But are there any key factors for improving voter turnout

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:20.880
that are, you know, just, like, hugely correlated with improving?

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:24.479
Or, yeah, I'm interested in maybe what some of the notes are.

00:18:24.479 --> 00:18:30.719
Yeah, so one of the – there is this line of research called social pressure,

00:18:30.719 --> 00:18:33.439
which basically is, like, we are – we, as humans,

00:18:33.439 --> 00:18:37.280
are very susceptible to what other people are doing.

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:40.640
And so – and again, I kind of got out of this world in 2016,

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.839
so this was the state of the art in, like, 2016, which is now quite old.

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:48.239
But at least at that point, people – this had sort of been fully internalized,

00:18:48.239 --> 00:18:51.439
but, like, everybody was using these sort of social pressure techniques,

00:18:51.439 --> 00:18:53.520
which basically are, like, every – you know,

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:56.640
three out of four of your neighbors voted in this last election.

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:58.239
Are you going to vote in this election?

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:01.599
And it's sort of this sense that, like, everybody is voting.

00:19:01.599 --> 00:19:03.040
It is your civic duty.

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:04.079
You should go out and vote.

00:19:04.079 --> 00:19:09.920
And that – at least among any of the sort of get-out-and-vote messages that people tried,

00:19:10.479 --> 00:19:14.479
that one is a real winner, you know, showing people's – you know,

00:19:14.479 --> 00:19:16.959
like, showing your voter record versus your neighbors.

00:19:16.959 --> 00:19:18.719
And, like, your neighbors are more consistent voters.

00:19:18.719 --> 00:19:20.400
You should probably get out there and vote.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:22.719
People respond pretty strongly to that one.

00:19:24.239 --> 00:19:24.880
That's very cool.

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:27.920
And that's honestly, like, probably a more ethical one.

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:29.040
Yeah, yeah.

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:30.239
That seems pretty good to me, right?

00:19:30.239 --> 00:19:31.520
Like, yeah, you should go out and vote.

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:36.000
Even as somebody who has pretty strong preferences about who people vote for, like,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:36.880
you should go out and vote.

00:19:36.880 --> 00:19:37.920
It's a good thing.

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:39.680
It's part of your civic duty.

00:19:40.319 --> 00:19:45.280
And voting rates in this country are depressingly low, you know, turnout,

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:48.719
even in big elections is, what, 60, 70 percent?

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:52.880
Well, are they trending a specific direction?

00:19:52.880 --> 00:19:54.160
Or are they –

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:56.400
I'm not aware of that.

00:19:57.599 --> 00:20:03.680
Honestly, you know, I was very enmeshed in this through, you know, the winter of 2016

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:08.479
and then kind of decided that was – that was a good – it was a great period of my career.

00:20:08.479 --> 00:20:10.160
I learned a ton about data science.

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:13.839
It turns out that working for political campaigns is, like,

00:20:13.839 --> 00:20:17.119
really exhausting because everything is on fire all the time.

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:20.560
And I was very happy to move on from – I'm really glad I did it,

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:23.280
but I was also very happy to, like, move on out of that world.

00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:28.719
Also, the reality for me, at least, is that I enjoyed the work.

00:20:28.719 --> 00:20:33.280
I did – I personally did not – some people get really, like,

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:36.959
they just want to win elections and, like, getting out of bed to win an election,

00:20:36.959 --> 00:20:38.400
like, that – that wasn't me.

00:20:38.959 --> 00:20:40.719
I really enjoyed the data science of it.

00:20:40.719 --> 00:20:42.239
I thought that was really fascinating.

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:51.119
But ultimately, although I care a lot who wins, I did not find that the work of being,

00:20:51.119 --> 00:20:57.280
you know, trying to win elections was work that I found compelling enough to overcome

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:02.479
the fact that it was a – it was a pretty grueling pace, especially, you know, in cycle.

00:21:03.839 --> 00:21:06.640
Well, that makes a lot of sense to me.

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:13.199
I can imagine how – how, I guess, fast that moves,

00:21:13.199 --> 00:21:16.719
especially with, like, very specific and strict deadlines for when things happen.

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:22.000
I think that that is a really good segue to compare maybe your data science work

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.640
to what a solutions engineer does.

00:21:24.640 --> 00:21:25.119
Yeah.

00:21:25.119 --> 00:21:29.520
Because I think it's – most people are very familiar with what data work is.

00:21:29.520 --> 00:21:33.839
I mean, you painted a – quite a cool story about what your data work used to be.

00:21:33.839 --> 00:21:38.400
How does that differ from maybe a traditional solutions engineer role?

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:38.880
Yeah.

00:21:38.880 --> 00:21:42.000
So, I mean, it's interesting, right?

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.040
When I – when I came to RStudio, then Posit, right?

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:49.839
For people who are in the R community, I think it's easy to imagine, at least at the time,

00:21:49.839 --> 00:21:52.719
I think this is maybe less true than it was back then.

00:21:52.719 --> 00:21:56.400
But, like, at the time, it was, like, easy to imagine that all of RStudio was just, like,

00:21:56.959 --> 00:22:02.719
Hadley and JJ and, like, Winston and Joe hanging out and, like, writing open source packages.

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:05.520
That was what RStudio was, right?

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:10.479
It was, like, the RStudio IDE and Shiny and, like, that was kind of what we did.

00:22:10.479 --> 00:22:14.160
You know, and then I started working there, right?

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:15.439
It's a software company, right?

00:22:15.439 --> 00:22:16.640
We are a software company.

00:22:16.640 --> 00:22:22.239
We are, I think, somewhat – you know, we have a little bit of a unique take in that

00:22:22.239 --> 00:22:24.000
we're a public benefit corporation.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:29.040
We're really genuinely committed to furthering the creation of open source software and

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:30.640
furthering open source data science.

00:22:31.439 --> 00:22:33.760
So it's a really cool company to work for.

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:36.079
But at the end of the day, we are a software company.

00:22:36.079 --> 00:22:39.439
We have to do all the things that a software company does.

00:22:39.439 --> 00:22:45.599
Because, you know, I think underlying the way Posit works is this question of how do

00:22:45.599 --> 00:22:47.680
you fund open source software?

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:53.040
And there have been a lot of different models to try and fund open source software.

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:56.239
And the reality is, unfortunately, that most of them kind of suck.

00:22:56.239 --> 00:22:59.680
Like, you know, you can get out there and you can do grants.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:01.920
You can try and find a funder.

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:04.560
You can do, like, freemium stuff.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:07.760
You can do services on top of open source software.

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:10.079
And some of those work and can be sustainable.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:14.160
A lot of them are just not that sustainable.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:24.400
And so the model that Posit has adopted, right, is we have many engineers working on free

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:30.479
and open source stuff that we provide to the community, which is really cool.

00:23:30.479 --> 00:23:31.520
But then we need to pay for that.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:37.359
And so what we do is we have, right, professional products that we believe provide value over

00:23:37.359 --> 00:23:38.640
and above the open source software.

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:45.920
And in particular, the way we think about it at Posit is, you know, we really give away

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:50.959
all the stuff that an individual data scientist needs to be successful on their own.

00:23:51.680 --> 00:23:57.040
Where we charge for software is the things that teams and organizations need to adopt

00:23:57.040 --> 00:23:59.119
and succeed with open source at scale.

00:23:59.119 --> 00:24:02.319
And, you know, the reason for that is, like, if you're an individual person, if you're

00:24:02.319 --> 00:24:06.479
a student, if you're a hobbyist just doing stuff, like, you should just be able to do

00:24:06.479 --> 00:24:07.359
that, right?

00:24:07.359 --> 00:24:12.959
But if you're fundamentally achieving organizational value on open source software, right, that's

00:24:12.959 --> 00:24:16.079
where we say, hey, like, we're contributing a lot to this.

00:24:16.719 --> 00:24:20.239
You know, we want there to be a fair exchange of value here.

00:24:20.239 --> 00:24:24.160
And obviously, companies do get really far just using our open source stuff.

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:25.280
That's awesome.

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:30.880
A lot of organizations want a higher degree of security and stability.

00:24:30.880 --> 00:24:33.760
And honestly, they want somebody to yell at when it all breaks.

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:37.599
And so that's what we provide with our professional products.

00:24:37.599 --> 00:24:45.199
And that's sort of the solution engineering role is this really cool role where we work

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:50.959
with Posit prospect people who are considering our professional products or have purchased

00:24:50.959 --> 00:24:51.199
them.

00:24:51.839 --> 00:24:59.359
And we help them figure out how do the Posit products fit in to the ecosystem of other

00:24:59.359 --> 00:25:01.040
data things they are doing, right?

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:04.319
These days, nobody has one data product.

00:25:04.319 --> 00:25:09.040
And so we help them understand where does Posit fit into the stack that they already

00:25:09.040 --> 00:25:09.760
have.

00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:11.280
And then we help them implement it, right?

00:25:11.280 --> 00:25:14.400
We help them figure out how do I make authentication work?

00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:19.680
So the right people have access and the right people have access to the right data, you

00:25:19.680 --> 00:25:21.439
know, at the right time.

00:25:21.439 --> 00:25:29.359
How do we, you know, configure the system so that it's stable and doesn't like fall

00:25:29.359 --> 00:25:35.439
over when, you know, 100 users come on to use Posit Workbench or come on to look at

00:25:35.439 --> 00:25:36.079
a shiny app.

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:43.760
And so that's really the solutions engineering role is this really cool, it's a very technical

00:25:43.760 --> 00:25:47.439
role, but also like you work with people all day, every day.

00:25:47.439 --> 00:25:55.920
And I think it's a really cool role for people who, you know, really enjoy technical stuff,

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:59.920
but also enjoy working with people, enjoy talking to people, enjoy explaining things

00:26:00.479 --> 00:26:00.959
to people.

00:26:00.959 --> 00:26:04.400
So that was sort of a meandering path to get there.

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:07.680
But I want to set some context around, like, what does a solutions engineer do?

00:26:07.680 --> 00:26:12.800
Because it's a foreign role to a data scientist because it's really a role that comes out

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:16.079
of being a software company, not out of doing data science.

00:26:16.880 --> 00:26:23.680
Yeah, I mean, so where would you characterize the, like, where would the sales engineering

00:26:23.680 --> 00:26:29.119
role fall between like a data scientist or maybe like a client facing data scientist

00:26:29.119 --> 00:26:30.400
and like a salesperson?

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:31.760
Yeah, great question.

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:34.959
It's definitely, it's somewhere in between for sure.

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:41.760
I would say it's, it really depends on the role, right?

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:46.000
We have people who are doing more engagement with our sales team, and those people are

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:47.359
closer to sales, right?

00:26:47.359 --> 00:26:50.000
Most of what they are doing is they're putting together demos.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.439
They're putting together proof of concepts.

00:26:51.439 --> 00:26:56.560
They're helping organizations try the Posit software and figure out if it works for them.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:27:01.760
So it's still a very technical role, but ultimately the job is to help that company figure out,

00:27:01.760 --> 00:27:03.920
like, yes, Posit is the right choice for me.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:06.160
I'm going to pay you for the software.

00:27:06.959 --> 00:27:09.439
Then there are folks who are more on the post-sales side.

00:27:09.439 --> 00:27:13.839
And that is more of a, you know, enhancing adoption, making sure that the platform is

00:27:13.839 --> 00:27:14.719
really great.

00:27:14.719 --> 00:27:21.520
And so on the team, it's about 70, 30, 60, 40 between people who have a data science

00:27:21.520 --> 00:27:25.040
background and people have like an IT administration background.

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:28.319
Because to do this job well, you really need both parts.

00:27:28.319 --> 00:27:34.239
You need the data science to be able to understand what customers are trying to do with our product.

00:27:34.239 --> 00:27:36.719
So they, when they say like, yeah, I'm trying to deploy this model.

00:27:36.719 --> 00:27:40.880
And like, I want to like have it run when this Quarto doc runs and like push it out

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:41.439
to the system.

00:27:41.439 --> 00:27:44.640
Like you have to understand what all of that means.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:50.880
But a lot of the data, excuse me, the day-to-day work is really around how do I get the system

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:51.199
stable?

00:27:51.199 --> 00:27:52.959
How do I get the system up and running?

00:27:52.959 --> 00:27:54.800
You know, how does the Linux server need to work?

00:27:54.800 --> 00:27:56.719
How does the file server need to work?

00:27:57.599 --> 00:28:02.640
And so the day-to-day work is not a ton of data science, but a lot of us on the team

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:07.439
have this background in data science because it's what we're talking about all day, every

00:28:07.439 --> 00:28:07.599
day.

00:28:07.599 --> 00:28:12.160
We're helping data scientists articulate to the IT admins, hey, here's why we need to

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:15.839
set this up in this way, because like, that's how I'm able to do my work.

00:28:15.839 --> 00:28:20.479
And then we talk to the IT admins to help them translate with the data science folks

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:26.000
and sort of play this role of, you know, a little bit of translation.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.239
Sometimes there's a little bit of therapy in there too, depending on the organization.

00:28:30.959 --> 00:28:31.359
Yeah.

00:28:31.359 --> 00:28:36.000
I mean, surprisingly, it sounds to me very similar to like a consulting role.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:37.520
It's not dissimilar, yeah.

00:28:38.479 --> 00:28:42.719
Where you're kind of straddling, you're like getting the solution and you're helping to

00:28:42.719 --> 00:28:43.839
facilitate things.

00:28:44.719 --> 00:28:47.920
Not necessarily seeing things all the way through, like the company asked to take this

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:51.599
somewhere, but like, hey, like let's get you into the right place and continue.

00:28:51.599 --> 00:28:56.160
I mean, one of my early roles was fairly similar to that.

00:28:56.160 --> 00:29:01.839
So I came from management consulting into data science and that was like a transition

00:29:01.839 --> 00:29:04.160
point to me where I was doing technical things.

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:08.719
I had finished my master's in computer science at that time, but I was coming from a more

00:29:08.719 --> 00:29:10.000
traditional consulting side.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.800
And it's like, well, honestly, this is probably easier.

00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:17.920
It leverages more of my skills than necessarily just going straight into data science.

00:29:17.920 --> 00:29:22.400
And then obviously eventually did make that transition, but I really relish that type

00:29:22.400 --> 00:29:22.719
of work.

00:29:22.719 --> 00:29:23.680
It helped me understand.

00:29:24.319 --> 00:29:30.719
Yeah, I think, you know, for the kind of person who enjoys that, right, like consultative

00:29:30.719 --> 00:29:32.880
kind of work, I think this is a really awesome job.

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:35.920
So I love it.

00:29:35.920 --> 00:29:39.599
I think it's a really, really cool position to be in.

00:29:39.599 --> 00:29:44.160
You know, the other thing that I think is really cool about the way we do it at Posit

00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:50.239
at least is that the solutions engineering role is not, we're not just customer facing,

00:29:50.239 --> 00:29:50.400
right?

00:29:50.400 --> 00:29:57.520
We also, because we are in this unique position of being, you know, very technical, very

00:29:57.520 --> 00:30:00.719
knowledgeable about the products, very knowledgeable about data science, and we're

00:30:00.719 --> 00:30:02.479
spending all this time with customers.

00:30:02.479 --> 00:30:07.040
We just know a lot about what customers are trying to do, what they need, what their pain

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:07.599
is.

00:30:07.599 --> 00:30:12.160
And so we really think a lot about the responsibility to like take that and help other

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:13.680
people, other people at Posit, right?

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:17.599
Bring that back into the product, bring that back into our documentation, bring that back

00:30:17.599 --> 00:30:21.199
to the open source engineers and the professional product engineers.

00:30:21.199 --> 00:30:25.920
So that ultimately, right, what we learn doesn't get stuck in our heads and doesn't become

00:30:25.920 --> 00:30:31.439
sort of like, oh, we're going to fix it for this customer, but can over time, you know,

00:30:31.439 --> 00:30:34.560
make it better, make the docs, make the products better for everyone.

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:36.959
That's such a cool feedback loop.

00:30:36.959 --> 00:30:39.280
I don't think a lot of people really think about that as much.

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:45.760
Yeah, that to me is the, like that's the part of the job that I think is like makes it from

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:49.839
like, oh yeah, that's a cool job to like, oh, when I'm talking to people who are in

00:30:49.839 --> 00:30:52.800
the interview process, like I sort of say to them, I'm like, this is a big job.

00:30:53.359 --> 00:30:59.680
Like people who succeed at Posit in this role are excited about having a big job with a

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:07.280
lot of freedom where they just have the ability, they are asked to go try and, you know, improve

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:10.479
the products based on what they've learned from talking to customers.

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:15.359
I think people who thrive in the role find that exciting.

00:31:15.520 --> 00:31:17.280
I think everybody finds it terrifying when they start.

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:18.079
I certainly did.

00:31:19.359 --> 00:31:23.599
But, you know, people who thrive in the role find it both terrifying, but also invigorating

00:31:23.599 --> 00:31:24.800
and not paralyzing.

00:31:26.239 --> 00:31:29.040
Well, I think, so I've talked to JJ.

00:31:29.040 --> 00:31:33.839
I forget what episode number it was, but it seems like part of that is also a transition

00:31:33.839 --> 00:31:35.359
to doing more Python stuff.

00:31:35.359 --> 00:31:40.640
I mean, obviously very common language in the data community.

00:31:41.599 --> 00:31:45.439
You know, some of my basketball clients are using R and it's interesting to me because

00:31:45.439 --> 00:31:49.599
I'm like, you know, pretty like aggressively Python guy.

00:31:49.599 --> 00:31:55.280
But I'm wondering, obviously you're in a unique position going from RStudio to now

00:31:55.280 --> 00:31:57.760
having Shiny for Python and having some of these other options.

00:31:58.479 --> 00:32:02.160
What do you think the state of the language war is now?

00:32:02.959 --> 00:32:13.359
Yeah, I really think that we are in a spot where what language you choose to use, I mean,

00:32:13.359 --> 00:32:14.560
between Python and R, right?

00:32:14.560 --> 00:32:18.560
Like if you want to go write some C++, like you're doing a different thing entirely.

00:32:18.560 --> 00:32:24.640
But between Python and R, I really feel at this point, like a lot of it is style and

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:25.359
background.

00:32:25.359 --> 00:32:28.319
Like I think personally, I really love R.

00:32:29.040 --> 00:32:30.160
That's the background I come from, right?

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:32.160
I come from a social science background.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:38.239
I did two semesters of computer science in college, but like I'm not a computer scientist.

00:32:38.239 --> 00:32:44.079
And so like for me, R makes a lot of sense in the way it treats data.

00:32:44.079 --> 00:32:45.359
I really like the interface.

00:32:45.359 --> 00:32:46.959
I think the tidyverse is awesome.

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:51.680
I grew up using RStudio and learned a lot there.

00:32:54.079 --> 00:32:55.280
And so like that's great.

00:32:57.199 --> 00:32:59.439
I think there are some libraries in Python that are better.

00:32:59.439 --> 00:33:01.439
There's some libraries in R that are better.

00:33:01.439 --> 00:33:05.680
These days, I think that's the reason, like that's why you would choose one or the other,

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:09.280
or you're on a team that has standardized on one or the other.

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:13.599
The degree of interoperability, especially like if you look at like Quarto for creating

00:33:13.599 --> 00:33:17.520
interactive documents, you can go like one code chump to the next, different languages,

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:19.119
fine, no problem, right?

00:33:19.119 --> 00:33:24.079
You look at like the ability of in either R or Python to write an API to speak to the

00:33:24.079 --> 00:33:26.959
other one or like to something else entirely, fine, no problem.

00:33:27.839 --> 00:33:33.199
You know, I think recently, right, we released, is it now beta?

00:33:33.199 --> 00:33:39.359
The Positron IDE, which is a new IDE that sort of is growing off of what, you know,

00:33:39.359 --> 00:33:44.400
JJ and folks learned about building RStudio and creating a, you know, from the ground

00:33:44.400 --> 00:33:46.880
up multilingual data science thing.

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:50.319
And honestly, for me, and I know Python people feel differently.

00:33:50.319 --> 00:33:55.040
For me, the main reason I didn't want to do Python is like, I don't understand why people

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.079
like put up with Jupyter notebooks.

00:33:58.079 --> 00:34:00.079
Like y'all can have nice things too.

00:34:00.079 --> 00:34:00.719
I don't know.

00:34:00.719 --> 00:34:03.280
Like, I just think the RStudio IDE is so great.

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:04.319
I've always loved it.

00:34:04.319 --> 00:34:09.840
And maybe that's because I come from there, but I've like, I always struggled to get into

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:11.280
doing my work in a Jupyter notebook.

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:13.919
It just like never, never really worked for me.

00:34:13.919 --> 00:34:17.919
You know, it's funny you say that because I've never like actively used Jupyter.

00:34:17.919 --> 00:34:18.719
So what do you use?

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:24.239
So when I started writing in Python, I actually use Anaconda, which is like very,

00:34:24.239 --> 00:34:25.600
very similar to RStudio.

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:26.639
Sure, sure.

00:34:26.639 --> 00:34:28.399
And then people made fun of me for that.

00:34:29.040 --> 00:34:32.000
So I started using VS Code and I use VS Code now.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:37.520
And I think, I think VS Code, you have to install a lot of plugins to get the environment

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:38.000
right.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:45.040
But the funny thing is, is my VS Code setup runs very similar to how my Anaconda environment

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:46.080
was, or like my...

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:47.360
Have you tried Python yet?

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:50.879
It wasn't Anaconda, it was Spyder, Spyder not Anaconda, sorry, sorry.

00:34:50.879 --> 00:34:51.679
Spyder is very similar.

00:34:51.679 --> 00:34:52.800
Yes, yes it is.

00:34:52.879 --> 00:34:56.080
I tried Spyder and I was like, oh, this is cool.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:35:00.239
But it is not as baked as RStudio was at the time.

00:35:00.239 --> 00:35:01.439
Have you tried Positron yet?

00:35:02.320 --> 00:35:02.800
I haven't.

00:35:03.679 --> 00:35:07.040
I mean, so it's fundamentally a, like it's a VS Code.

00:35:07.760 --> 00:35:12.639
I don't know if it's a fork or what, how exactly you would describe its relationship to VS Code.

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:18.159
But it, for people who are comfortable in VS Code, it really like pulls downstream of

00:35:18.159 --> 00:35:25.120
that, but builds off of, right, the idea of a four-pane data science ID, which like, same

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:31.040
as Spyder or RStudio, but sort of modernized and based off of VS Code, which for the folks,

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:36.879
right, I'm, this is not my area of expertise, but like gave us a lot of things out of the

00:35:36.879 --> 00:35:40.000
box that in RStudio we had to build ourselves, right?

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:46.560
Like things like, as a very simple example, like coloring of code lines and that sort

00:35:46.560 --> 00:35:46.719
of thing.

00:35:46.959 --> 00:35:50.239
Like the kind of thing, like you just, you just get from open source VS Code.

00:35:50.239 --> 00:35:52.239
So if you haven't tried it, you might, you might want to.

00:35:52.239 --> 00:35:58.479
Yeah, that's where, honestly, the one thing I missed the most is being able to see all

00:35:58.479 --> 00:36:01.520
of the data frames that you have, like in working memory.

00:36:02.399 --> 00:36:09.520
And that was 100%, like the single largest factor where, why Spyder was very appealing

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:09.760
to me.

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:13.040
And now I operate without it, but I feel like you'd like to learn to live without it.

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:13.360
Yeah.

00:36:13.360 --> 00:36:18.000
So anyway, I mean, that was, so to go back to your original question, like, you know,

00:36:18.879 --> 00:36:23.919
to me, it's just like, it's, it's more, and the other thing I didn't mention, right, is

00:36:23.919 --> 00:36:31.600
obviously like Arrow and other, you know, storage formats that allow basically symmetric

00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:33.280
access from R and Python.

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:36.320
And so you can just like save and parquet or whatever.

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:38.159
And like, it's fine, right?

00:36:38.159 --> 00:36:39.439
Like you get actually nice, right?

00:36:39.439 --> 00:36:43.199
It's not like saving in CSV where like, then you import and everything kind of, you know,

00:36:43.199 --> 00:36:47.040
you got to like recast all your dates and stuff, you know, but like, it like actually

00:36:47.040 --> 00:36:47.360
works.

00:36:48.479 --> 00:36:54.080
And so I think like, increasingly, it's an interface level, the language is an interface

00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:54.320
level.

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:59.040
And like, I think that's going to become even more true as LLMs become more and more

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:04.000
capable in this regard that it really is going to come down to some combination of personal

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:04.560
preference.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:10.159
And like, there's this or that package that happens to work better, right?

00:37:10.159 --> 00:37:15.520
Like, I don't know, at least as of a couple, I have not kept up with like natural language

00:37:15.520 --> 00:37:16.320
processing very much.

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:22.320
But like, as of a couple of years ago, right, the NLTK in Python was like a better natural

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:25.199
language processing library than anything I thought there was in R.

00:37:25.199 --> 00:37:28.000
And so like, if you were doing that, I'd be like, yeah, go use Python.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.159
I think that's the kind of thing where it's going to come down to is there are going to

00:37:30.159 --> 00:37:34.800
be sort of esoteric packages for doing this particular task or that particular task that

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:36.639
might be better in R or Python.

00:37:36.639 --> 00:37:40.239
But other than that, I think it's really going to come down to what interface do you

00:37:40.239 --> 00:37:40.800
like better?

00:37:41.919 --> 00:37:45.679
I think I 100% agree with that sentiment.

00:37:45.679 --> 00:37:55.360
I mean, for example, I remember doing PCA in R was just so much better than in Python.

00:37:55.360 --> 00:38:03.040
Granted, not really a tool I use very often, but I was willing to like basically relearn

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:07.360
R every time I had to do PCA just because I didn't like using the Python libraries that

00:38:07.360 --> 00:38:08.239
were there.

00:38:08.239 --> 00:38:15.360
And just as you said, I think a lot of the AI tools we have now democratize the process

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.600
or like the analysis to whatever language operates.

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:20.239
Yeah.

00:38:20.239 --> 00:38:24.719
I'm actually a little, and I'm curious what you think and what you've seen about this,

00:38:24.719 --> 00:38:30.800
but I'm actually a little concerned on that front because the way these LLMs work, right,

00:38:30.800 --> 00:38:33.679
they are good at a lot of basic tasks.

00:38:33.679 --> 00:38:39.280
And I feel like you still need an expert to look at it and make sure it's doing what you

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:40.399
think it's doing.

00:38:40.399 --> 00:38:48.320
And I do wonder if like, it introduces this at least question of like, how do junior people

00:38:48.959 --> 00:38:50.159
get their start?

00:38:50.159 --> 00:38:54.719
If like, if you're able to do a lot of the stuff that a junior data scientist would do,

00:38:54.719 --> 00:39:00.560
if an LLM can kind of do that, how do you get over that hump to like being able to then

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:05.360
review what the LLM wrote and really like really knowing like, yep, what it wrote, like

00:39:05.360 --> 00:39:09.679
that was what I meant or like, oh shoot, that was not really what I meant.

00:39:09.679 --> 00:39:11.280
Like, try again, Claude.

00:39:12.959 --> 00:39:19.439
That feels like an unsolved problem to me of like, it's cool that it can do some of

00:39:19.439 --> 00:39:26.080
these different kinds of tasks, but it still feels to me like there's a need for expert

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:28.959
eyes on it to make sure it's doing what you want.

00:39:28.959 --> 00:39:35.040
And I'm not sure how you get that exposure in a world where like LLMs are, you know,

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:38.399
not today, but like in five years kind of territory.

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:42.399
So I think as they are right now, agree 100%.

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:48.639
Basically, we need a lot of the stuff that produces is wrong, or it doesn't work, or

00:39:48.639 --> 00:39:51.919
it's like, I had an issue where I was writing some code.

00:39:51.919 --> 00:39:54.239
And when I ran it on my machine, I just got different results.

00:39:54.879 --> 00:39:57.919
And I was like, why is this happening?

00:39:58.959 --> 00:40:00.239
Basically, a name was misspelled.

00:40:00.239 --> 00:40:01.280
And I was like, okay, fine.

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:08.560
Like, yeah, but I'm a little less concerned because I think that it allows people to iterate

00:40:08.560 --> 00:40:10.959
faster and see dramatically more code.

00:40:10.959 --> 00:40:11.360
Sure.

00:40:11.360 --> 00:40:20.479
And that evens out that eventually, because there are going to be bugs in the code, you're

00:40:20.479 --> 00:40:21.600
going to be getting bad results.

00:40:21.600 --> 00:40:25.679
And like, frankly, you're not going to have a job if you're producing bad results.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:29.040
You know, there is a compromise.

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:34.639
And so inevitably, I think sort of the market corrects itself that, hey, after you make

00:40:34.639 --> 00:40:37.600
a couple of mistakes, you start scrutinizing it really carefully.

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:42.159
And then you can actually use it as a tool for debugging itself in the sense that like,

00:40:42.159 --> 00:40:43.760
hey, like, why is it this way?

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:46.000
Why did you choose that rather than this decision?

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:47.360
Are there other ways to do this?

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:53.679
I think I believe a lot of those problems can be solved with good prompting.

00:40:54.239 --> 00:40:59.679
And by good prompting, I mean, asking questions of what is being built and having it break

00:40:59.679 --> 00:41:00.239
itself down.

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:04.399
That's also a skill I think that has to be cultivated.

00:41:04.399 --> 00:41:06.479
So it's not something that comes out of the gate.

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:17.280
But that's, you know, I'm, especially with people who are learning, I think they will

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.320
give up before they come over-reliant on it because they'll have problems with what's

00:41:22.320 --> 00:41:24.879
being created as well.

00:41:24.879 --> 00:41:26.959
So that's sort of where I fall.

00:41:26.959 --> 00:41:30.560
But I think it's still a legitimate, a completely legitimate concern.

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:31.600
Yeah, it's interesting.

00:41:32.399 --> 00:41:33.840
That makes a lot of sense to me.

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:39.919
I think one of the things I'm concerned about, and we got like, what, we're like 40 minutes

00:41:39.919 --> 00:41:40.000
in.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.320
This is the first time I'm mentioning my book, DevOps for Data Science.

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:49.679
But like, in the book, right, one of the things I talk about is that, you know, like, if you're

00:41:49.679 --> 00:41:54.239
doing regular software engineering, there's basically like, one kind of correctness you

00:41:54.239 --> 00:41:54.479
care about.

00:41:54.479 --> 00:41:59.919
It's basically like, does it run in a performant enough way?

00:41:59.919 --> 00:42:03.199
Like, if your software does that, and you're doing sort of general purpose software engineering,

00:42:03.199 --> 00:42:04.639
like, it's fine, right?

00:42:04.639 --> 00:42:07.520
Like, like, Zoom needs to run.

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:10.879
And like, when it runs, then like Zoom or Excel works, right?

00:42:10.879 --> 00:42:15.120
But like, when you're talking about data science, there's this second sense in which it needs

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:18.560
to work, which is like, the answers need to be correct.

00:42:19.439 --> 00:42:22.800
And they need to be what you meant them to be, right?

00:42:22.800 --> 00:42:30.959
And like, the problem with that is that unlike, unlike the way you can write unit tests for

00:42:30.959 --> 00:42:39.199
a software stack, it's very difficult to write testing for actual results in data science,

00:42:39.199 --> 00:42:42.719
because usually, like, you wouldn't be doing it if you knew what the answer was.

00:42:42.719 --> 00:42:44.959
And you could just run it and make sure you got the right answer.

00:42:44.959 --> 00:42:48.959
And so I think, like, what you're saying makes a lot of sense to me.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:53.919
It is still scary to me that probably you're going to find out those mistakes by like,

00:42:53.919 --> 00:42:55.919
putting them in front of somebody who is an expert.

00:42:55.919 --> 00:42:58.479
And they'll be like, this, this number makes, I mean, we've all been, right?

00:42:58.479 --> 00:43:00.080
Like, this number makes no sense.

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:01.439
We've all heard that.

00:43:01.439 --> 00:43:03.040
It's like, oh, geez, what have I done?

00:43:04.479 --> 00:43:10.959
But, you know, but like, but like, there's a second level of, of, of correctness that

00:43:10.959 --> 00:43:15.760
you care about in data science that isn't there in pure software engineering that I think,

00:43:16.879 --> 00:43:21.360
you know, makes that, that sort of self-correcting piece a little scarier,

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:24.479
I think, for a data scientist, whereas like, if you're just writing code,

00:43:24.479 --> 00:43:25.600
if it doesn't run, it doesn't run.

00:43:25.600 --> 00:43:27.919
Or if it like takes too long, it takes too long.

00:43:27.919 --> 00:43:32.159
But like, you know, in data science, like your, your data merge can

00:43:32.159 --> 00:43:35.600
work in some sense of the word, but completely screw up your data

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:36.159
along the way.

00:43:36.159 --> 00:43:38.639
And you may not realize that for a long time, which is.

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:39.280
Yeah.

00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:40.959
There's not like binary outcomes.

00:43:40.959 --> 00:43:41.199
Right.

00:43:41.199 --> 00:43:41.439
Yeah.

00:43:41.439 --> 00:43:44.879
Where it's like, yes or no, it's, uh, this is sort of right.

00:43:44.879 --> 00:43:46.000
Or this is sort of wrong.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:46.239
Yeah.

00:43:46.239 --> 00:43:50.719
Or you can, you can, code can run and give you completely the wrong answer.

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:53.760
Or like do something you, you don't intend, right?

00:43:53.760 --> 00:43:58.320
Like there was that whole thing a few years ago in, about in scikit-learn,

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:03.280
like the default for a lasso regression made it actually a, do you remember this?

00:44:03.280 --> 00:44:07.840
Like it, it was that like the default value for some type of regression

00:44:07.840 --> 00:44:09.280
was not what people thought it was.

