and, and look at it.

00:45:51.679 --> 00:45:52.000
Yeah.

00:45:53.040 --> 00:46:01.679
So, you know, talking about the book, talking about the nature of, I guess, like DevOps

00:46:01.760 --> 00:46:02.879
in the data science space.

00:46:03.520 --> 00:46:08.399
Can you explain maybe what that actually means and how that might be different from, for

00:46:08.399 --> 00:46:11.280
example, MLOps, which is talked about quite a bit?

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:11.520
Yeah.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:22.959
So, you know, fundamentally DevOps is a set of practices, procedures, and, and tools,

00:46:22.959 --> 00:46:23.679
sort of, right?

00:46:23.679 --> 00:46:27.280
So here's like, I'm going to, I'm going to digress here and tell a little history, right?

00:46:27.280 --> 00:46:33.120
So you're like in the nineties and, um, right, at least according to these stories, which

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:37.600
I believe are completely apocryphal, everybody is writing their software using the waterfall

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:40.159
method where you like spend a year gathering requirements.

00:46:40.159 --> 00:46:44.560
You spend two years writing software and then voila, it doesn't do what you thought, right?

00:46:44.560 --> 00:46:46.320
Like that's the like waterfall story.

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:49.600
I'm somewhat doubtful that that ever actually happened, but like, that's the story.

00:46:50.159 --> 00:46:53.360
And so then come up comes the rise of agile, right?

00:46:53.360 --> 00:46:57.919
The agile software movement, which is like this idea that you're going to, instead of

00:46:57.919 --> 00:47:01.760
trying to like do a year of requirements gathering and two years of building, you're going to

00:47:01.760 --> 00:47:02.719
build small increments.

00:47:02.719 --> 00:47:04.000
You're going to deliver quickly.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:08.560
And like, fundamentally, while agile is a development method, it's also a method of

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:11.280
like checking that you're doing the right thing, right?

00:47:11.280 --> 00:47:15.040
Because you're frequently going back to your customer, whether that's a customer, customer,

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:17.439
an internal customer, and you're saying like, does this do what you want to do?

00:47:17.439 --> 00:47:18.239
Is this the right thing?

00:47:18.239 --> 00:47:19.280
Is this the right thing?

00:47:19.280 --> 00:47:25.360
But there's a problem, which is you can write the code that does, you know, creates this

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:25.919
thing.

00:47:25.919 --> 00:47:28.320
But like, how do you then deliver it, right?

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:31.919
You have to put it into production somehow to get it in front of those people.

00:47:32.639 --> 00:47:35.439
And if you're doing this right before you did that, like once, right?

00:47:35.439 --> 00:47:40.879
It was like you spent a year gathering requirements, two years building, and then six months putting

00:47:40.879 --> 00:47:42.639
into production, but it was like one time.

00:47:42.639 --> 00:47:46.879
But now, you know, like if you're, if you're talking about a major code base, like Facebook,

00:47:46.879 --> 00:47:53.679
right, like, they, they push, I think, like it's thousands of updates a week to their

00:47:53.679 --> 00:47:57.679
code base, and they go live on the site, like they're constantly just pushing updates.

00:47:57.679 --> 00:48:04.959
And so a system that requires, you know, six months to check that a release is good to

00:48:04.959 --> 00:48:09.040
go just, I mean, that's not going to work if you're trying to release, you know, even

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:14.639
if it's once a month, right, which is a slow release cadence for a lot of products, like

00:48:14.639 --> 00:48:16.080
that's completely untenable.

00:48:16.719 --> 00:48:18.239
If, if it takes too long to get it right.

00:48:18.239 --> 00:48:24.560
So DevOps is this system of tools, procedures, processes, so that you can build the software

00:48:24.560 --> 00:48:28.560
to make it easy to put into production and put things into production in a way that they're

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:30.959
going to be safe, secure, observable.

00:48:30.959 --> 00:48:32.560
You can see what they're doing.

00:48:32.560 --> 00:48:36.639
You can understand what happens when they go wrong, recreate the error and try and fix

00:48:36.639 --> 00:48:37.840
it on the code side.

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:42.639
And so it's basically trying to bring closer together the development, the dev, and the

00:48:42.639 --> 00:48:44.800
day-to-day running of the software, the, the ops, right?

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:45.919
So that's, that's where it comes from.

00:48:45.919 --> 00:48:48.879
It's a, it's a sort of pure software engineering kind of concept.

00:48:49.840 --> 00:48:54.959
And so, you know, as might not be surprising, given how I described with what the solutions

00:48:54.959 --> 00:49:00.639
engineer role is, like, that's what I spend my time discussing with our customers.

00:49:00.639 --> 00:49:04.800
Like, how do you take data science and put it into production?

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:06.320
How do you make it production grade?

00:49:06.320 --> 00:49:08.159
How do you like write code that is ready for production?

00:49:08.159 --> 00:49:10.800
Then how do you actually put it into production?

00:49:11.360 --> 00:49:14.800
And a lot of that is lessons from DevOps or they're an interpretation of DevOps.

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:18.639
And, you know, it's tempting, I think, for people who are software engineers to be like,

00:49:18.639 --> 00:49:23.600
you just do DevOps, but you should just do it in R or Python.

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:24.719
And I think that's really wrong.

00:49:24.719 --> 00:49:30.159
Like, I think fundamentally data science is a different thing than software engineering.

00:49:30.159 --> 00:49:36.800
Like the analogy I draw is like, if, if software engineering is like architecture, data science

00:49:36.800 --> 00:49:38.000
is like archeology.

00:49:38.639 --> 00:49:42.879
Like, like they're, you're, you're doing something in both cases, but they're very different.

00:49:43.439 --> 00:49:49.040
And the way you think about building software, and if you're doing data science, like you're

00:49:49.040 --> 00:49:54.320
building software, even if you don't like it, or if you're bad at it, like you're building

00:49:54.320 --> 00:49:54.800
software.

00:49:55.520 --> 00:50:00.080
And so that's really what, what the book was, was a reaction to was observing that people

00:50:00.959 --> 00:50:06.639
knew a lot about data science, about, you know, machine learning, about, you know,

00:50:06.639 --> 00:50:12.959
statistics about, you know, sort of like graphical design and these sorts of things.

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:18.399
But then they got really stumped when it came time to put it actually into production.

00:50:18.399 --> 00:50:22.959
And so the book is sort of split into three parts, where the first part is really about,

00:50:22.959 --> 00:50:29.120
like, how do you write your code, your R or Python code in a way that makes it easy to

00:50:29.120 --> 00:50:30.879
put it into production when the time comes?

00:50:30.879 --> 00:50:36.879
How do you think ahead to, like, how do I, how do I, you know, put it into production

00:50:36.879 --> 00:50:37.679
eventually?

00:50:37.679 --> 00:50:38.800
How do I make it secure?

00:50:38.800 --> 00:50:39.840
How do I make it stable?

00:50:39.840 --> 00:50:43.199
How do I make sure it scales on bigger data sets and these sorts of things?

00:50:44.320 --> 00:50:49.439
The second section of the book is the part that I really didn't want to write, but I

00:50:49.439 --> 00:50:54.959
kind of felt like I had to, which is like, if you have to manage the server that's hosting

00:50:54.959 --> 00:50:56.639
all this, like, how do you, how do you do that?

00:50:56.639 --> 00:50:58.000
How do you manage a server?

00:50:58.000 --> 00:50:59.600
How do you manage a database?

00:50:59.600 --> 00:51:00.959
What the hell is up with Docker?

00:51:00.959 --> 00:51:04.399
Like, you know, those, those kinds of questions, which I think a lot of us end up facing.

00:51:04.399 --> 00:51:08.320
I think most data scientists at some point in their career have to answer these questions,

00:51:09.280 --> 00:51:10.959
but are really lost about where to start.

00:51:10.959 --> 00:51:12.479
So that's sort of the middle section of the book.

00:51:12.479 --> 00:51:16.320
And then the last section of the book is about, okay, you're working at a big company that

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:19.439
has an IT admin organization.

00:51:19.439 --> 00:51:21.280
It's a sophisticated IT admin organization.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.560
What concerns are they going to have about the work you're doing?

00:51:24.560 --> 00:51:31.760
And how do you communicate with them about the, the, the work that you need to do and

00:51:31.760 --> 00:51:36.479
make sure that they understand what you need from them and give, giving them what, what

00:51:36.479 --> 00:51:40.000
they need from you so that you can create a great environment to do data science.

00:51:42.080 --> 00:51:42.639
I love that.

00:51:43.600 --> 00:51:53.040
So let's, I also think that's a very important like gap that is filled.

00:51:54.560 --> 00:51:57.360
So my hypothesis and correct me if I'm wrong.

00:51:57.360 --> 00:52:03.919
So DevOps for data science, it probably encorpuses more of the pipeline than just MLOps.

00:52:03.919 --> 00:52:04.399
That's right.

00:52:05.360 --> 00:52:06.239
You did ask about that.

00:52:06.239 --> 00:52:12.479
So to me, I mean, MLOps is such an interesting, like to me, MLOps is just this like, and I

00:52:12.479 --> 00:52:17.439
don't know, there's been so much hype around it, but like it's this tiny narrow slice of

00:52:17.439 --> 00:52:21.760
the pie, which is like, once you've built a machine learning model, how do you serve

00:52:21.760 --> 00:52:23.280
that machine learning model?

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:25.360
And then how do you, you know, do things like horse racing them?

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:32.719
And I'm being a little like glib about it, but to me, it's such a, a small part of the

00:52:32.719 --> 00:52:34.320
work you need to do as a data scientist.

00:52:34.320 --> 00:52:39.199
And at least in my observation, there are organizations that have sophisticated MLOps

00:52:39.840 --> 00:52:48.000
needs, but they're much rarer than organizations that like have a dashboard in R or a, you

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:52.159
know, some sort of image processing pipeline in Python.

00:52:52.159 --> 00:52:54.399
And they need to somehow productionize that.

00:52:54.399 --> 00:52:57.840
And maybe there's a machine learning model somewhere in there, but there's like a whole

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:00.000
data management pipeline on one end.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:04.479
There's a whole downstream pipeline of people or systems who need to consume these things.

00:53:04.479 --> 00:53:11.280
And so there's a lot of understanding around the narrow slice that I think of as MLOps,

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:16.959
which is really about like building and serving machine learning models, which, you know,

00:53:16.959 --> 00:53:21.520
I mean, I think is an important but narrow part of the job of a data scientist.

00:53:21.520 --> 00:53:24.320
I mean, unless, you know, if you work at Netflix, right?

00:53:24.320 --> 00:53:29.280
Like there are just straight ML engineers at Netflix and that's awesome if you can get

00:53:29.280 --> 00:53:34.560
that job, but like most data scientists are doing a lot more than just building machine

00:53:34.560 --> 00:53:35.600
learning models.

00:53:35.600 --> 00:53:39.679
And particularly if you want to deliver value, there's so many other things you have to do

00:53:39.679 --> 00:53:42.000
than just building and serving machine learning models.

00:53:43.520 --> 00:53:44.399
Yeah, I get it.

00:53:44.399 --> 00:53:54.239
So what in terms of the DevOps for data science, what do you think is the most overlooked aspect

00:53:54.879 --> 00:53:55.760
of that process?

00:53:56.399 --> 00:53:56.719
Yeah.

00:53:56.719 --> 00:54:02.479
I mean, this is the like unsexy answer, but to me, it's the people.

00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:08.320
It's that fundamentally what you're doing is you are a person who is working with other

00:54:08.320 --> 00:54:14.000
people to try and do something that is valuable to your organization or to the world.

00:54:14.159 --> 00:54:20.239
And so, you know, there are tools, there are systems, but fundamentally what you're trying

00:54:20.239 --> 00:54:25.360
to do is to work with other people to get something, hopefully something cool, done.

00:54:26.479 --> 00:54:31.120
And so to me, and I see this particularly from junior folks, right?

00:54:31.120 --> 00:54:37.840
When I, my first job managing a data science team, I was working with some folks who were

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:40.719
just a couple of years out of college and they would be doing a lot of different kinds

00:54:40.719 --> 00:54:44.000
of work and they'd be like, when do we get to do the data science?

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:46.320
Like, when do we get to build the models?

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:52.320
And I'd be like, well, if what we want to do is provide value to our organization, ultimately

00:54:52.320 --> 00:54:53.199
that's what matters.

00:54:53.760 --> 00:54:58.159
We have to be focused on understanding what is valuable to the organization, what is valuable

00:54:58.159 --> 00:54:59.760
to the people in the organization.

00:55:00.399 --> 00:55:04.800
And then there's a lot of like relationship building to get that done.

00:55:04.800 --> 00:55:10.239
And so, you know, that's why my favorite section of the book by far is the third section of

00:55:10.239 --> 00:55:12.560
the book, which does not have any code in it.

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:20.159
It's all just like helping, helping people understand what it is that IT admins are concerned

00:55:20.159 --> 00:55:23.360
when they, when they're talking about security, like what are they, what do they care about

00:55:23.360 --> 00:55:24.879
when they're talking about authentication?

00:55:24.879 --> 00:55:27.040
What do they care about when they're talking about stability?

00:55:27.040 --> 00:55:28.239
What do they actually care about?

00:55:28.239 --> 00:55:32.800
Because to me, that's when data scientists can have the best outcomes is when the data

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:37.120
scientists are able to do data science and when they can communicate effectively with

00:55:37.120 --> 00:55:43.919
other people who are concerned about all these sort of production-y things and not

00:55:43.919 --> 00:55:45.199
having sort of crosswords.

00:55:45.199 --> 00:55:49.040
But you need to be able to communicate with each other and need to understand what those

00:55:49.040 --> 00:55:51.760
people care about, like what keeps them up at night.

00:55:51.760 --> 00:55:55.520
It's probably not, you know, did you add that extra feature to your model?

00:55:55.520 --> 00:55:58.159
That's probably not the thing that keeps them up at night.

00:55:58.879 --> 00:56:02.000
Although it might be what keeps you up at night as a data scientist and communicating

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:10.000
about that I think is the easiest part to overlook because it's right, like people go,

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:10.879
they're technical people.

00:56:10.879 --> 00:56:12.719
We want technical solutions.

00:56:12.719 --> 00:56:18.320
We like the elegance of, you know, APIs fitting together like puzzle pieces and like, but

00:56:18.320 --> 00:56:22.239
then you have to like go talk to the person who's going to like put the API into your

00:56:22.239 --> 00:56:24.320
like, you know, production system.

00:56:24.879 --> 00:56:26.719
And that, that's, that's a people problem.

00:56:26.719 --> 00:56:30.719
And that's, that's always, that's always going to be mushier than just writing a bunch of

00:56:30.719 --> 00:56:31.219
code.

00:56:32.399 --> 00:56:33.360
I like that answer.

00:56:33.360 --> 00:56:39.040
It's a little harder to write or research or talk about the mushier side of things.

00:56:39.760 --> 00:56:43.679
And I'm excited that your book connects those two so elegantly.

00:56:45.520 --> 00:56:47.919
I would love, I'm excited to read the book.

